<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Original Research</div>
    <h1>Valero Energy (VLO)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of Valero Energy — using normalized cash flows to smooth refining cyclicality.</p>
    <span class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: StockAnalysis</span>
    <span class="compiled-by">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</span>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="dcf-wrapper">
  <!-- VERDICT -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV !== null ? roundedIV.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice !== null ? currentPrice.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- METRICS -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${latestRevenue !== null ? (latestRevenue / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">TTM/FY Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${normalizedBaseFcf !== null ? (normalizedBaseFcf / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Normalized FCF (5y Avg)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${latestEps !== null ? latestEps.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${netCash !== null ? (netCash / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- METHODOLOGY -->
  <h2>Methodology: Normalizing the Cyclicality</h2>
  <p>Oil refining is notoriously cyclical. Peak years produce massive cash windfalls, while trough years can barely cover capex. A standard DCF using the latest year's Free Cash Flow will wildly misprice the asset depending on where we are in the cycle. To adjust for this, we use a <strong>normalized base Free Cash Flow</strong> by taking the 5-year average.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Normalize Base Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Instead of using the most recent year, we average the last 5 years of FCF. Valero's 5-year average FCF is <strong>${(normalizedBaseFcf/1000).toFixed(1)} billion</strong>. This smooths out the massive peaks of recent years and the troughs of earlier periods, giving us a "through-the-cycle" cash generation baseline.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project Conservative Growth (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project this normalized FCF will grow at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% annually</strong> for 5 years. While Valero is a best-in-class operator, the refining sector is mature, and growth will come primarily from optimization and renewable diesel (DGD), not massive capacity expansion.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate Terminal Value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume a terminal growth rate of <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(0)}%</strong>. This is below GDP growth, reflecting the long-term secular headwinds facing fossil fuels due to EV adoption, offset by Valero's low-cost advantage and renewable fuels business.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount at Required Rate</h4>
      <p>Cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</strong>. This is derived mathematically: 10Y Treasury (4.18%) + Beta (${beta}) × Equity Risk Premium (5.5%). We round slightly to reflect the cyclical risk profile and leverage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ASSUMPTIONS -->
  <h2>Assumptions & Rationale</h2>
  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">Applied to the 5-year normalized FCF base, not the peak. 2% growth reflects minor capacity creep, cost optimization, and growth in the higher-margin renewable diesel segment (Diamond Green Diesel). Refining is a mature, capital-intensive business, so high sustained FCF growth is unrealistic.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">Based on a 10Y Treasury yield of 4.18%, an ERP of 5.5%, and Valero's beta of ${beta}. The 9.5% rate demands a healthy premium over risk-free assets to compensate for the extreme volatility of refining margins (crack spreads).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">1% terminal growth is conservative. It assumes that while gasoline/diesel demand may slowly decline in the developed world over the next few decades, Valero's low-cost, highly complex Gulf Coast refineries will be the last to shut down, capturing market share from less efficient competitors.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

