  <!-- RISKS -->
  <h2>Risks to the Valuation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Crack Spread Volatility:</strong> Valero's profits are entirely dependent on the difference between the price of crude oil and the price of refined products (the crack spread). A prolonged period of narrow crack spreads would decimate FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>EV Transition:</strong> Accelerated adoption of electric vehicles could structurally reduce demand for gasoline and diesel faster than anticipated, turning the terminal growth rate negative.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory & Environmental Costs:</strong> Refineries are subject to strict environmental regulations, including Renewable Identification Numbers (RINs) compliance costs, which can act as a massive drag on margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> Refineries require constant, heavy maintenance capital expenditures. An unexpected turnaround or accident at a major facility (like Port Arthur) can wipe out a quarter's cash flow.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 5-year normalized FCF instead of TTM FCF?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Refining is highly cyclical. Using peak FCF from a blowout year makes the company look artificially cheap, while using trough FCF makes it look expensive. Averaging FCF over 5 years (a typical cycle length) provides a more accurate picture of the company's long-term cash-generating power.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the terminal growth rate so low (1%)?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While Valero is an excellent operator, the long-term volume demand for traditional refined fossil fuels faces secular headwinds due to the energy transition. Assuming growth beyond 1% in perpetuity for a traditional refinery is aggressive.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the renewable diesel business factor in?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Valero's Diamond Green Diesel (DGD) joint venture is a major bright spot, providing higher margins and growth that offsets traditional refining cyclicality. This is baked into our assumption that normalized FCF can still grow at 2% despite broader industry headwinds.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

